{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493059"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:54:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:54:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1210"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1210"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.25,0.61,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1210"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105625"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1210"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1210"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88060"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2137"},{"type":"tags","id":"2996"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3516"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2073"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42248"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105625"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department in a confused state. Her daughter states that her mother seems to have been rather lethargic over the last couple of days and had fallen over on a couple of occasions. When she went into her bedroom this morning, her mother was disorientated and mumbling. She was unaware of where she was, so the daughter decided to bring her straight to hospital. The patient drinks about 4 - 5 standard drinks a day and has recently been started on hydrochlorothiazide for hypertension. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, apart from her disorientation in time and space, the patient does not have any abnormal signs on physical examination. Her blood pressure is 140/80 mmHg and pulse rate 90/min. Her laboratory results are shown:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum sodium 112 mmol/L (135 - 145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum potassium 2.7 mmol/L (3.5 - 5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum chloride 90 mmol/L (95 - 110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine osmolality 630 mOsm/kg (50 - 1,200)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine sodium 13 mmol/L (\u0026gt; 20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluid restriction","Isotonic saline (0.9%) + potassium supplementation","Hypertonic saline (3%) + potassium supplementation","Furosemide 20mg IV","Oral sodium and potassium supplementation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of chronic, severe, symptomatic hyponatraemia. This has likely resulted from her recently starting a thiazide diuretic. Hyponatraemia secondary to thiazide use typically presents within the first two weeks of commencing the medication, but can also be triggered by concurrent renal pathology, other medications, changes in water/salt intake or illness. These patients may appear euvolaemic or hypovolaemic. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere hyponatraemia needs to be corrected to prevent complications including raised ICP, seizures and coma. The patient should be monitored in an intensive care unit with frequent measurement of serum sodium and cautious replacement with \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E to avoid rapid correction and subsequent osmotic demyelination syndrome. Other factors which increase her risk of osmotic demyelination syndrome include her high alcohol intake and hypokalaemia. Potassium should also be replaced intravenously to prevent cardiovascular sequelae. Given the rapid changes in electrolytes, osmolality and fluid shifts, hypertonic saline should generally be administered in the ICU.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is used in hypervolaemic or euvolaemic asymptomatic patients and is insufficient to correct the above scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsotonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat asymptomatic hyponatraemia, or in cases of hypovolaemia. It will not correct the deficit fast enough given the severity of clinical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiuretics such as \u003Cstrong\u003Efurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E are inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral sodium and potassium supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E are valid options for an asymptomatic presentation however this woman requires more urgent care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypertonic saline should be given to correct severe symptomatic hyponatraemia."],"references":["Sterns RH. Treatment of severe hyponatremia. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2018 Apr 6;13(4):641\u2013649. doi: 10.2215/CJN.10440917. Available at: https://doi.org/10.2215/CJN.10440917","Hwang KS, Kim GH. Thiazide-induced hyponatremia. Electrolyte Blood Press. 2010 Jun;8(1):51-7. doi: 10.5049/EBP.2010.8.1.51. Epub 2010 Jun 30. Erratum in: Electrolyte Blood Press. 2012 Dec;10(1):35-6. PMID: 21468197; PMCID: PMC3041494. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3041494/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88060"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1210"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88060"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T09:15:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-11T09:15:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1210"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105625"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"des